[[File:McKeldinTents.jpg|right|thumb|300px|[[Occupy Baltimore]] protesters at McKeldin Square]]
'''McKeldin Square''' is an area of [[Downtown Baltimore]], located near the [[Inner Harbor]] at the corners of [[Pratt Street|Pratt]] and [[Light Street|Light]] Streets.

The central area is a polygon of brick. On the Pratt St. side there is a strip of grass; behind the brick there is a pool at the base of a multi-leveled concrete structure with walkways and fountains.<ref>{{cite book |title=Aquatecture: architecture and water |last=Wylson |first=Anthony |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1986 |publisher=Architectural Press |location= |isbn= |page=63 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Cultural facilities in mixed-use development |last=Snedcof |first=Harold R. |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1985 |publisher=Urban Land Institute |location= |isbn= |page=236 |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>

The location of the square puts it right in the middle of Baltimore's [[Baltimore riot of 1861|1861 riots]], during which locals turned on a Union regiment that was passing through the city.

McKeldin Square has been designated as Baltimore's zone for protests, where it is legal to exercise one's [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights and pass out pamphlets.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spray-paint artist arrested at Inner Harbor |first=Andrea K. |last=Walker |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2011-09-18/news/bs-md-oc-artist-arrested-20110918_1_ocean-city-paint-spray |newspaper=The Baltimore Sun |date=September 18, 2011 |accessdate=17 November 2011}}</ref> Permits are required for groups with groups of 25 or more requiring a permit. On October 4, 2011, it became the location of the [[Occupy Baltimore]] protests until their December 13 eviction.

